com:
Hey folks, what did I think of “Indiana Jones And The Secret Of Life”?
Well, I’ll tell ya:

“Indiana Jones And The Secret Of Life” is a great new installment in the long-running franchise. Harrison Ford is back as Indy in the late 1960s. He’s hung up the whip after settling down with Marian, however, Indy’s son Mutt Williams, now recast with Jai Courtney as the character (who seems to have a knack for these kinds of films, playing John McClain’s son in last year’s Die Hard sequel and Kyle Reese in next year’s Terminator 5), who is now an adventurer of his own, asks his father to help him investigate a strange occurrence in the North Pole. Indy is initially reluctant but agrees and goes with his son.
After going into a cave there they are taken by a couple of radiant beings through some tunnels to a vast underground city, numerous crystalline structures, with floating vehicles. Indy remarks that maybe Admiral Byrd’s encounters weren’t so fanciful after all. They are taken to the ruler of the cities, Sandra Bullock’s character Ulyssia. After some conversations, Indy asks who these people are and where they have been, having been around for thousands upon thousands of years. Ulyssia tell Indy that they are a spiritually advanced race that created humanity, first with Adamuos and Evelyn. The reason for their absence from humanity and their lack of willingness to help is because they have become depressed with what humanity has done and believe they are incapable of being saved.

1/2
